<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Adrianne Goodman 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 BIT OF IRISH: Ventura County can claim a lot of local ties to the Emerald Isle 
. . . One of every five residents in half the county's cities boasts some Irish 
ancestry . . . Many of those with a bit of the Irish in them -- along with 
thousands of other county residents -- are expected to attend the ninth annual 
County Ventura St. Patrick's Day parade Saturday at 10 a.m. in downtown Ventura 
. . . As always, the wearing of the green is mandatory. 
</P>
<P>
 DIGESTING THE TEST: The results of a new statewide student-testing system 
aren't going down well in some districts where the scores were low (A1) . . . 
One day after the state released results of the California Learning Assessment 
System, some school officials are coming up with a host of complaints about the 
test, including criticism of its rigorous standards . . . In Oxnard, skeptical 
officials will devise their own version of the test in eighth-grade math (B1) . 
. . "We need to know whether our students can do basic math," said Supt. Norman 
R. Brekke. 
</P>
<P>
 SEISMIC SAFETY: The Jan. 17 earthquake has pushed plans to retrofit bridges 
across the state -- including 45 in Ventura County -- into fast forward (B1) . 
. . Caltrans officials said a proposal already in place to strengthen the 
bridges will be accelerated because of the collapse of six major roadways 
during the quake . . . All of Ventura County's 322 highway bridges withstood 
the quake. 
</P>
<P>
 FARM HONORS: Some of Ventura County's oldest farming families will be honored 
by the California Women for Agriculture of Ventura County . . . The group will 
hold a March 17 dinner for family members and descendants of George Morton 
Richardson and George Washington Faulkner in Santa Paula and Henry Mayo Newhall 
in Piru . . . This is the ninth year the dinners have been held, said group 
President Donna Pinkerton. And given the county's deep farming roots, she said, 
"we've still got families to go." Where the Irish Are 
</P>
