<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA031194-0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 021635 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
March 11, 1994, Friday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 2; Column 1; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
111 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY: SECURITIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Regulators Offer Brochure on Investing: The Securities and Exchange 
Commission, stock exchanges, municipal securities regulators and state 
regulators announced the publication of a pamphlet with information designed to 
help consumers identify the decisions to be made before investing, select a 
broker and handle any problem that may arise. "There's no small print in it and 
the language is blunt," SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt told a Washington news 
conference. Among other things, the brochure advises consumers to steer clear 
of "guarantees" that they will not lose money on a particular transaction or 
claims that they can double their money in six months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
