<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: LAGUNA BEACH; LAKE RESTORATION PROPOSAL ADVANCES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LESLIE EARNEST 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A plan to begin restoring the only three natural lakes in Orange County has 
been forwarded to the county and Laguna Beach for review, a prelude to gaining 
funding that could help pay for the project. 
</P>
<P>
 The cleanup plan for the three basins, located in Laguna Canyon within the 
Laguna Coast Wilderness Park, was presented Wednesday night at a meeting of the 
Coastal Greenbelt Authority, a group formed to manage the park. 
</P>
<P>
 The proposal calls for cleaning the lakes' algae-ridden waters, uprooting 
invasive shrubbery and replanting natural vegetation to attract migrating 
wildlife. Proponents hope to launch the project by fall. 
</P>
<P>
 "If we can bring back this vegetation and clean up the water, we will get back 
an enormous amount of bird life, much more than we have now," said biologist 
Elisabeth Brown, an authority member who presented the plan to the group of 
about 40 people. 
</P>
<P>
 Robert G. Fisher, director of the county's harbors, beaches and parks 
division, said that a state grant may be available to help pay for the first 
phase of work and that the county should apply by May if it hopes to secure the 
funding. 
</P>
<P>
 The county manages the Laguna Coast Wilderness Park, a 2,500-acre swath of 
open space at the edge of Laguna Beach that is expected eventually to expand to 
10,000 acres and become the county's largest park. Laguna Beach owns the lakes. 
</P>
<P>
 The three ponds, which range in size from 1.5 acres to 12 acres, are suffering 
from a variety of maladies, including soil erosion and water pollution. 
</P>
<P>
 The goal is to revive the lakes under a two-phase, $900,000 plan, and in time 
to allow additional public access to the park, which is now open only one 
weekend per month for docent tours. 
</P>
<P>
 Some parts of the second phase could be done only if Laguna Canyon Road, which 
borders two of the lakes, is realigned. The lake restoration plan is part of a 
larger, $2.5-million proposal designed by Wetlands Research Associates Inc., a 
San Rafael consulting firm. LESLIE EARNEST 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
