<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAILING; ELIAS CONFRONTS ACCUSER TODAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICH ROBERTS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Mike Elias is a sailor, not a figure skater, but Australia's Neville Wittey 
might consider wearing knee pads today when the two meet to conclude the first 
round robin of the Congressional Cup at Long Beach.  
</P>
<P>
 Elias, who represents the host Long Beach Yacht Club, was still bitter after 
Thursday's racing about having Wednesday's victory over Steve Grillon taken 
away on a protest by Wittey, who was in a different race. 
</P>
<P>
 "In race-car circles, there's a Richard Petty, and here there's petty Wittey," 
Elias said at the postrace news conference. "I'm going to race him in the 
morning and that's going to be a lot of fun."  
</P>
<P>
 Elias, like most locals, has been overmatched by the world-class competitors 
in five previous Congressionals. So it hurts to have any victory taken away, 
especially on a protest by someone in another match. RICH ROBERTS 
</P>
</TEXT>
